headline: IN LONDON, THE 'DESIGN WARS'
content:
LEAD: In establishing retail beachheads on the Thames, a one-time public-relations man from Argentina, a Dane who was once an oilman and a former haircutter from Casablanca have skirmished with their predecessors and each other, embroiling London in what might be called ''designer wars.''
In establishing retail beachheads on the Thames, a one-time public-relations man from Argentina, a Dane who was once an oilman and a former haircutter from Casablanca have skirmished with their predecessors and each other, embroiling London in what might be called ''designer wars.''
The spoils belong to fashion consumers, because this city, where shopping for designer clothes was once a one-stop affair, is now brimming with name-brand boutiques.
Until the designer wars began, Browns on South Molton Street was London's Buckingham Palace of fashion. Its owners, Joan and Sidney Burstein, first brought many stars of international clothing design to London, where often, Browns was their exclusive outlet.
But today, Giorgio Armani has his name on his own London shop. It is owned by the Dane, Peder Bertelsen, who was recently crowned the city's ''most powerful fashion entrepreneur'' by The London Standard. Mr. Bertelsen's company operates a bumper crop of other London boutiques, including Ungaro, Valentino, Katharine Hamnett, Krizia, Walter Steiger, Luciano Soprani and Comme des Garcons Homme Plus.
London now has four Gianni Versace shops, too, They are co-owned by the Argentinian, Roberto Devorik. So are Gianfranco Ferre's three boutiques and five Regine and Regine Uomo shops (including one in Los Angeles), which sell designer lines such as those of Montana, Mugler, Blass, de la Renta, Kamali and Genny.
For more extreme as well as more moderately priced fashion, young Londoners turn to the Moroccan, Joseph Ettedgui, who, with his two brothers, owns an empire of 21 establishments (including shops in Paris and New York). Joseph, as he is universally known, sells clothes by Britain's Richmond-Cornejo team and the Japanese designers Kenzo and Yohji Yamamoto in their own boutiques, as well as his own labels. Joseph sells housewares, too, in his Pour La Maison boutiques, which also carry clothes by Rifat Ozbek and Azzedine Alaia. Joseph also owns two restaurants, L'Express and Joe's Cafe.
The latter is on London's newest fashion front line, the crossroads of Brompton Road and Draycott Avenue. The latest Joseph store, a three-story emporium, opened there this fall, as did Mr. Bertelsen's first Katharine Hamnett shop, a dramatic store in a former garage, which is billed as the largest one-floor, one-designer boutique in Europe.
Joseph, a perpetually unshaven cigar smoker, came to London as a hair stylist in 1959. In 1964, he began selling designer clothes in his salon. Soon, that sideline became his main business. ''Very few people were doing this,'' Joseph recalled. London's fashion scene, he continued, ''wasn't as cutthroat as it is now.''
In 1974, Joseph opened a Kenzo boutique. By 1978, he had shops all over London. ''Nothing was planned,'' Joseph said. ''Whenever I felt people were bored with one thing, I opened another.'' By the mid-80's, Joseph's empire had grown to include a wholesale operation and three small shops called Chinese Laundry, selling designs by Katharine Hamnett. 'A Bit Angry'
But last year, Ms. Hamnett broke from Joseph and got her larger shop from Mr. Bertelsen. ''We felt a bit angry'' over the designer's defection, Joseph said. ''There is a competition, but I try to ignore it,'' he continued. ''It is not an easy business.'' Hard feelings have become a byproduct of London's fashion business. ''The mistake we have all made,'' Mr. Devorik observed, ''was to go along with the ego trips of designers.''
Mr. Devorik probably knows the most of the three about the designing ego. His grandmother owned a couture salon in his native Buenos Aires. ''I was born in haute couture,'' said the dapper retailer, who usually wears the Versace designs he sells. ''I drank Coca-Cola at Coco Chanel.''
After a stint in his late teens as a publicity agent for Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer in Buenos Aires, Mr. Devorik moved to London and opened a cashmere shop near the Victoria and Albert Museum ''because the tourist buses stopped there,'' he said. ''I gave a commission to the guides and a discount to the customers.'' He also traveled to Italy, where he forged relationships with Krizia and a young designer, Gianni Versace.
In 1974, Mr. Devorik joined forces with the owner of a London shop called Regine, Semiramis Karacen, the wife of a publisher in Istanbul, Turkey. It sold French designers. Soon they were selling Mr. Devorik's Italians, too. By the end of the decade they had opened their first Versace boutique. For a time, Regine Uomo, their men's store, also carried Armani. But, Mr. Devorik said, when he was offered a chance to add the Armani women's line that had been exclusive to Browns in exchange for giving the designer his own boutique, he declined. Mr. Bertelsen said yes.
In 1982, Mr. Bertelsen was an investment adviser to a Middle Eastern oil company. Among its investments was a Colorado ranch, Mr. Bertelsen said, and his first contact with fashion came when he was approached by Ralph Lauren, who wanted to buy the property. In exchange, Mr. Bertelsen said, he was offerred Mr. Lauren's European distribution and his London shop, which had been part of Browns.
''I didn't know what I was doing,'' Mr. Bertelsen said, so his year-long association with Mr. Lauren ''didn't work out very well.''
But one thing he learned was that most designers wanted their own shops, not boutiques within larger retail operations. So through contacts he had established, Mr. Bertelsen won the right to open London shops for several designers, including Giorgio Armani.
''We put Armani on the map,'' Sidney Burstein said. ''We had him for 12 years. We spent $:100,000 refurbishing our Armani shop. Three months later, he took it away.'' Mr. Bertelsen also lured several employees from Browns. In the three years since, they have given Mr. Bertelsen a fashion education.
''I had to learn from scratch,'' he said. But his company, Aguecheek Ltd., named for Sir Andrew Aguecheek in ''Twelfth Night,'' nonetheless became a major force in British fashion. Besides the ''name'' boutiques, it operates Gallery 28, which sells new designers, and a discount outlet. Aguecheek co-owns London's branch of Tiffany's, and it also backs several British designers, including Alistair Blair and John Galliano. But Mr. Bertelsen still seems more comfortable with balance sheets than ballgowns.
''I spend more time thinking than going into shops,'' he said. ''Clothes, oil and potatoes are commodities.''
In that vein, he has said that if Ms. Hamnett's shop should not do well, he will move her clothes out and something else in. But at least the commodities he's now trading are British designers, which may be a canny public-relations move to offset his image as a Johnny-come-lately invader. Despite that, The Sunday Times of London recently called him ''only marginally more popular than Attila the Hun.''
''The English,'' Mr. Devorik observed, ''are suspicious of success.''
